There is an extensive history of drought and famine in Africa and it
is continuing. Twenty-seven million people are now facing famine.

Millions have died. Some governments have refused relief supplies for
portions of their countries under rebel control, thus increasing
famine deaths.

U.S. donations to Africa run into the millions. Because of the
enormity of the problem, donor countries have difficulty in keeping up
with requests.

The U.S. is debating about attaching strings to aid. Military forces
in Africa have seized some food supplies for themselves and these
forces keep the governments in power.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT921-3939"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E">   

International experts are being sent to southern Africa to assess the
effects of a severe drought on food supplies. Ten drought-stricken
countries are affected with Zimbabwe and South Africa in the most
severe condition.

These two countries, normally food exporters, must now import
substantial amounts of grain. It has been described as the worst
drought of the century, with about 15 million people at
risk. Additionally, the northeast of Africa, including Sudan,
Ethiopia, Somalia, and Djibouti, has also felt the drought.

The U.S. State Department believes that a huge donor assistance
program will be needed to avoid the crisis.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
