South Africa's drought could adversely affect grain production and
cancel out the expected recovery in economic growth, according to the
country's agricultural minister. He predicted earlier that hot and dry
conditions in southern Africa could cause widespread famine.

The United Nations Food and Agriculture organization said that the
expected shortfall would be four million tons.
q
Of the countries facing famine, Mozambique and Zambia, in addition to 
Zimbabwe and South Africa, were the most in danger. 

The countries facing famine do not have adequate rail and port
facilities, complicating the distribution of food to needed areas.
</SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT921-8958"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E">
   
The older generation of South Africa's farmers say that the drought of
1992 is the worst since 1933.

Especially hard hit are the farmers who produce South Africa's main
crop, maize; stock farmers are also badly affected.

In 1933, drought forced farmers off their land. The state says that it
will prevent this from happening this time.

Imports of food could reach record levels, thereby compounding the
deficit problem. Unemployment caused by the drought, a depressed
economy and flat growth rate could add significantly to the state's
dilemma.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT921-2956"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E">   

Prieska is a desert farming community in northern South Africa's Cape
Province. It was the site of Friday's annual agricultural show.

South Africa's minister of agriculture is also a farmer. Kraii van
Niekerk was campaigning in his constituency. He was trying to convince
his fellow farmers to continue political reform and adopt his own
farming techniques because of the drought.

His platform is one of minimizing the number of farmers going bankrupt
by offering loans, writing off debt and obtaininig subsidies.

To permit a large number of farms to fail would result in
unemployment, thus exasperating the food problem.  </SUM>
    
<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT922-10715"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E">  
 
Farmers are taking stock in Zimbabwe. They are totaling losses in the
face of the worst drought they have ever experienced. Rainfall in 1992
has been less than half the usual amount.

The production of maize, a staple crop, is about 90 percent less than
normal.  Soybeans, winter wheat and cotton production is a fraction of
the usual totals.  Only drought-resistant tobacco is at normal
levels. Farm production for 1992 has decreased to the lowest level in
30 years.

Zimbabwe needs 350 million dollars worth of imported food. Water
shortages are having a serious effect on electric power
production. </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890914-0207"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E">   

According to President Quett Masire of Botswana, industrial nations
can assist in relieving Africa's drought and subsequent hunger by
making a greater effort at reducing global warming. Masire and
Dr. Bernard Ledea Ouedraogo, an anti-hunger organizer in Burkina Faso,
were awarded the 1988 Africa Prize for Leadership for their
anti-hunger efforts.

Although a severe drought afflicted Africa from 1981 to 1987, not one
person in Botswana died of drought-induced famine.

Dr. Ouedraogo, the other prizewinner, organized the peasants in nine
African countries. As a result, new crop-raising techniques were
learned, erosion was checked, forests replanted and health care
improved.  </SUM>
